# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flour
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flour/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:flour/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:flour/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:flour/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:flour/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:flour/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:flour/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:flour/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:flour/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:flour/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:flour/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:flour/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:flour/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:flour/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:flour/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:flour/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:flour/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:flour/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:flour/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:flour/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:flour/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:flour/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:flour/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:flour/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:flour/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:flour/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:flour/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:flour/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:flour/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:flour/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:flour/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:flour/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:flour/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:flour/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:flour/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:flour/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:flour/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:flour/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:flour/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:flour/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:flour/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:flour/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:flour/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:flour/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:flour/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:flour/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:flour/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:flour/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:flour/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:flour/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:flour/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:flour/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:flour/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:flour/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:flour/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:flour/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:flour/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:flour/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:flour/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] An **advance-fee scam** is a form of fraud and is a common scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scam works by promising the victim a large sum of money in return for a small upfront payment, which the fraudster claims will be used to obtain the large sum.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] If a victim makes the payment, the fraudster either invents a series of further fees for the victim to pay or simply disappears.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] It is popularly known as "yahoo yahoo" in Nigeria.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The number "419" refers to the section of the Nigerian Criminal Code dealing with fraud.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scam has been used with fax and traditional mail and is now prevalent in online communications such as emails.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Other variations include the Spanish Prisoner scam and the black money scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Although Nigeria is most often the nation referred to in these scams, they mainly originate in other nations.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Other nations known to have a high incidence of advance-fee fraud include Ivory Coast, Togo, South Africa, the Netherlands, Spain, and Jamaica.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The modern scam is similar to the Spanish Prisoner scam that dates back to the late 18th century.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In that con, businessmen were contacted by an individual allegedly trying to smuggle someone who is connected to a wealthy family out of a prison in Spain.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer promised to share money with the victim in exchange for a small amount of money to bribe prison guards.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] One variant of the scam may date back to the 18th or 19th century, as a very similar letter, entitled "The Letter from Jerusalem".
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This is illustrated in the memoirs of Eugène François Vidocq, a former French criminal and private investigator.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Another variant of the scam, dating back to ca.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] 1830, appears very similar to emails today: "Sir, you will doubtlessly be astonished to be receiving a letter from a person unknown to you, who is about to ask a favour from you..." and goes on to talk of a casket containing 16,000 francs in gold and the diamonds of a late marchioness.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The modern-day transnational scam can be traced back to Germany in 1922 and became popular during the 1980s.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] There are many variants of the template letter.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] One of these, sent via postal mail, was addressed to a woman's husband to inquire about his health.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] It then asked what to do with profits from a $24.6 million investment and ended with a telephone number.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Other official-looking letters were sent from a writer who said he was a director of the state-owned Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] He said he wanted to transfer $20 million to the recipient's bank account—money that was budgeted but was never spent.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In exchange for transferring the funds out of Nigeria, the recipient would keep 30% of the total.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] To get the process started, the scammer asked for a few sheets of the company's letterhead, bank account numbers, and other personal information.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Yet other variants have involved mention of a Nigerian prince or other member of a royal family seeking to transfer large sums of money out of the country—thus, these scams are sometimes called "Nigerian Prince emails".
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The spread of e-mail and email harvesting software significantly lowered the cost of sending scam letters by using the Internet in lieu of international post.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Although Nigeria is most often the nation referred to in these scams, they may originate in other nations as well.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] For example, in 2007, the head of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission stated that scam emails more frequently originated in African countries or in Eastern Europe.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Within the European Union, there is a high incidence of advance-fee fraud in the Netherlands and Spain.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The emails sent invariably feature a large number of implausible claims, as well as numerous spelling and grammatical mistakes.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Nigeria has a reputation for being at the center of email scamming.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Modern variations include “sugar daddy/sugar momma” schemes, some of which involve advance-fee scamming, and money flipping, whereby the mark is promised a large amount of money in exchange for sending a small amount of money.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A 2018 study of Nigerian hip-hop culture found that glamorization of cyber-fraud is prevalent in such music.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some scammers have accomplices in the United States and abroad who move in to finish the deal once the initial contact has been made.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Many scammers tend to come from poorer and more-educated backgrounds, where Internet access and better education, along with inability to afford basic necessities, drive people into committing online fraud.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They could also have been influenced by social media celebrities and artists who promote scamming as a "cool" trend to quickly gain access to luxury items like sports cars and fashion.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In the case of Nigeria, the rise in scamming cases was due to a boom in cybercafes, a series of economic crashes from the 1980s, and the resulting joblessness among young people in Nigeria.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This scam usually begins with the perpetrator contacting the victim via email, instant messaging, or social media using a fake email address or a fake social media account.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The fraudster then makes an offer that would allegedly result in a large payoff for the victim.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] An email subject line may say something like "From the desk of barrister [Name]", "Your assistance is needed", "Important", "Dear Sir or Madam" and so on.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The details vary, but the usual story is that a person, often a government or bank employee, knows of a large amount of unclaimed money or gold that they cannot access directly, usually because they have no right to it.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The money could be in the form of gold bullion, gold dust, money in a bank account, blood diamonds, a series of cheques or bank drafts, and so on.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The sums involved are usually in the millions of dollars, and the investor is promised a large share, typically ten to fifty percent, in return for assisting the fraudster to retrieve or expatriate the money.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Although the vast majority of recipients do not respond to these emails, a small percentage do, enough to make the scam worthwhile as many millions of messages can be sent daily.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] To help persuade the victim to agree to the deal, the scammer often sends one or more false documents that bear official government stamps, and seals.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] 419 scammers also often utilize fake websites and addresses to present themselves as more legitimate.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Multiple "people" may write or be involved in schemes as they continue, but they are often fictitious; in many cases, one person controls all the fictitious personae used in scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Once the victim's confidence has been gained, the scammer then introduces a delay or monetary hurdle that prevents the deal from occurring as planned, such as "To transmit the money, we need to bribe a bank official.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Could you help us with a loan?" or "For you to be a party to the transaction, you must have holdings at a Nigerian bank of $100,000 or more" or similar.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This is the money being stolen from the victim; the victim willingly transfers the money, usually through some irreversible channel such as a wire transfer, and the scammer receives and pockets it.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Often but not always, delays and additional costs are added by the fraudster, always keeping the promise of an imminent large transfer alive, convincing the victim that the money the victim is currently paying would be covered several times over by the payoff.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Sometimes psychological pressure is added by claiming that the scammers' side, to pay certain fees, had to sell belongings and mortgage a house or by comparing the salary scale and living conditions in their country to those in the West.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Much of the time, however, the needed psychological pressure is self-applied: once the victims have provided money toward the payoff, they feel they have a vested interest in seeing the "deal" through.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some victims even believe they can cheat the other party, and walk away with all the money instead of just the percentage they were promised.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The essential fact in all advance-fee fraud operations is that the promised money transfer to the victim never happens because the money does not exist.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer disappears, and the victim is left on the hook for the money sent to the scammer.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] During the course of many schemes, scammers ask victims to supply bank account information.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Usually this is a "test" devised by the scammer to gauge the victim's gullibility; the bank account information is not used directly by the scammer, because a fraudulent withdrawal from the account is more easily detected, reversed, and traced.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Scammers instead usually request that payments be made using a wire transfer service like Western Union and MoneyGram.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The reason given by the scammer usually relates to the speed at which the payment can be received and processed, allowing quick release of the supposed payoff.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The real reason for using such money-sending services is that such wire transfers are irreversible and often untraceable.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Further, these services are ideal because identification beyond knowledge of the details of the transaction is often not required, making receipt of such funds almost or entirely anonymous.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] However, bank account information obtained by scammers is sometimes sold in bulk to other fraudsters who wait a few months for the victim to repair the damage caused by the initial scam before raiding any accounts that the victim did not close.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Telephone numbers used by scammers tend to come from burner phones.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In Ivory Coast, a scammer may purchase an inexpensive mobile phone and a pre-paid SIM card without submitting any identifying information.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] If the scammers believe they are being traced, they discard their mobile phones and purchase new ones.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The spam emails used in these scams are often sent from Internet cafés equipped with satellite internet connection.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Recipient addresses and email content are copied and pasted into a webmail interface using a stand-alone storage medium, such as a memory card.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Certain areas of Lagos, such as Festac Town, contain many cyber cafés that serve scammers; cyber cafés often lock their doors during certain times, *e.g.*, between 10:30 p.m. and 7:00 a.m., so that scammers inside may work without fear of discovery.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Nigeria also contains many businesses that provide false documents used in scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] After a scam involving a forged signature of Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo in summer 2005, Nigerian authorities raided a market in the Oluwole section of Lagos.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] There, police seized thousands of Nigerian and non-Nigerian passports, 10,000 blank British Airways boarding passes, 10,000 United States Postal money orders, customs documents, false university certificates, 500 printing plates, and 500 computers.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The "success rate" of the scammers is also hard to gauge, since they operate illegally and do not keep track of specific numbers.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] One individual estimated that he sent 500 emails per day and received about seven replies, citing that when he received a reply, he was 70 percent certain he would get the money.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] If tens of thousands of emails are sent every day by thousands of individuals, it does not take a very high success rate to be worthwhile.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The success of advance fee crimes is based on the initial persuading of the victim.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The FBI reported that in 2019 there were 14,607 US citizens that were victims of advance fee scams, which collectively represented in excess of $3.5 billion worth of lost funds.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In recent years, efforts have been made by governments, internet companies, and individuals to combat scammers involved in advance-fee fraud and 419 scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2004, the Nigerian government formed the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC) to combat economic and financial crimes, such as advanced-fee fraud.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2009, Nigeria's EFCC announced that they had adopted smart technology developed by Microsoft to track down fraudulent emails.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They hoped to have the service, dubbed "Eagle Claw", running at full capacity to warn a quarter of a million potential victims.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some individuals participate in a practice known as scam baiting, in which they pose as potential targets and engage the scammers in lengthy dialogue so as to waste the scammer's time and decrease the time they have available for actual victims.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Likewise, the website Artists Against 419, set up by volunteers, offers a public database with information on scam websites.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They work closely together with APWG to share their data with financial institutions and cybersecurity companies.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A central element of advance-fee fraud is that the transaction from the victim to the scammer must be untraceable and irreversible.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Otherwise, the victim, once they become aware of the scam, could successfully retrieve their money and alert officials who could track the accounts used by the scammer.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Cryptocurrencies or wire transfers via Western Union and MoneyGram are ideal for this purpose.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] International wire transfers cannot be cancelled or reversed, and the person receiving the money cannot be tracked.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Other non-cancellable forms of payment include postal money orders and cashier's cheques, but wire transfer via Western Union or MoneyGram is more common.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Since the scammer's operations must be untraceable to avoid identification, and because the scammer is often impersonating someone else, any communication between the scammer and his victim must be done through channels that hide the scammer's true identity.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The following options in particular are widely used.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Because many free email services do not require valid identifying information and also allow communication with many victims in a short span of time, they are the preferred method of communication for scammers.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some services go so far as to mask the sender's source IP address (Gmail being a common choice), making the scammer's country of origin more difficult to trace.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] While Gmail does indeed strip headers from emails, it is possible to trace an IP address from such an email.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Scammers can create as many accounts as they wish and often have several at a time.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In addition, if email providers are alerted to the scammer's activities and suspend the account, it is a trivial matter for the scammer to simply create a new account to resume scamming.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some fraudsters hijack existing email accounts and use them for advance-fee fraud purposes.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] For instance, with social engineering, the fraudster impersonates associates, friends, or family members of the legitimate account owner in an attempt to defraud them.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A variety of techniques such as phishing, keyloggers, and computer viruses are used to gain login information for the email address.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Facsimile machines are commonly used tools of business whenever a client requires a hard copy of a document.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They can also be simulated using web services and made untraceable by the use of prepaid phones connected to mobile fax machines or by use of a public fax machine such as one owned by a document processing business like FedEx Office/Kinko's.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Thus, scammers posing as business entities often use fax transmissions as an anonymous form of communication.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This is more expensive, as the prepaid phone and fax equipment cost more than email, but to a skeptical victim, it can be more believable.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Abusing SMS bulk senders such as WASPs, scammers subscribe to these services using fraudulent registration details and paying either via cash or with stolen credit card details.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They then send out masses of unsolicited SMS messages to victims stating they have won a competition, lottery, reward, or an event and that they have to contact somebody to claim their prize.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Typically, the details of the party to be contacted will be an equally untraceable email address or a virtual telephone number.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] These messages may be sent over a weekend when the staff at the service providers are not working, enabling the scammer to be able to abuse the services for a whole weekend.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Even when traceable, they give out long and winding procedures for procuring the reward (real or unreal) and that too with the impending huge cost of transportation and tax or duty charges.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The origin of such SMS messages is often from fake websites/addresses.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Mid-2011 saw the innovation of scammers employing premium rate callback numbers for potential victims to reply to (rather than providing a website or email address).
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] On calling the number, the victim is first reassured that 'they are a winner' and then subjected to a long series of instructions on how to collect their 'winnings'.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] During the message, there will be frequent instructions to 'ring back in the event of problems'.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The call is always 'cut off' just before the victim has the chance to note all the details.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some victims call back multiple times in an effort to collect all the details.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer thus makes their money out of the fees charged for the calls.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Many scams use telephone calls to convince the victim that the person on the other end of the deal is a real, truthful person.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer, possibly impersonating a person of a nationality or gender other than their own, would arouse suspicion by telephoning the victim.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In these cases, scammers use TRS, a US federally funded relay service where an operator or a text/speech translation program acts as an intermediary between someone using an ordinary telephone and a deaf caller using TDD or other teleprinter device.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer may claim they are deaf, and that they must use a relay service.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The victim, possibly drawn in by sympathy for a disabled caller, might be more susceptible to the fraud.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] FCC regulations and confidentiality laws require operators to relay calls verbatim and adhere to a strict code of confidentiality and ethics.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Thus, no relay operator may judge the legality and legitimacy of a relay call and must relay it without interference.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This means the relay operator may not warn victims, even when they suspect the call is a scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] MCI said about one percent of their IP Relay calls in 2004 were scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Tracking phone-based relay services is relatively easy, so scammers tend to prefer Internet Protocol–based relay services such as IP Relay.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In a common strategy, they bind their overseas IP address to a router or server located on US soil, allowing them to use US-based relay service providers without interference.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] TRS is sometimes used to relay credit card information to make a fraudulent purchase with a stolen credit card.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In many cases however, it is simply a means for the con artist to further lure the victim into the scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Sometimes, victims are invited to a country to meet government officials, an associate of the scammer, or the scammer themselves.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some victims who travel are instead held for ransom.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Scammers may tell a victim that they do not need a visa or that the scammers will provide one.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] If the victim does this, the scammers have the power to extort money from the victim.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Sometimes victims are ransomed, kidnapped, or murdered.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] State Department report, over fifteen persons were murdered between 1992 and 1995 in Nigeria after following through on advance-fee frauds.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 1999 Norwegian millionaire Kjetil Moe was lured to South Africa by scammers and was murdered.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] George Makronalli was lured to South Africa and was killed in 2004.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] There are many variations on the most common stories, and also many variations on the way the scam works.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some of the more commonly seen variants involve employment scams, lottery scams, online sales and rentals, and romance scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Many scams involve online sales, such as those advertised on websites such as Craigslist and eBay, or property rental.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This article cannot list every known and future type of advanced fee fraud or 419 scheme; only some major types are described.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Additional examples may be available in the *external links* section at the end of this article.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This scam targets people who have posted their résumés on job sites.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer sends a letter with a falsified company logo.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The job offer usually indicates exceptional salary and benefits, and requests that the victim needs a "work permit" for working in the country, and includes the address of a (fake) "government official" to contact.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The "government official" then proceeds to fleece the victim by extracting fees from the unsuspecting user for the work permit and other fees.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A variant of the job scam recruits freelancers seeking work, such as editing or translation, then requires some advance payment before assignments are offered.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Many legitimate (or at least fully registered) companies work on a similar basis, using this method as their primary source of earnings.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer contacts the victim to interest them in a "work-from-home" opportunity, or asks them to cash a cheque or money order that for some reason cannot be redeemed locally.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In one cover story, the perpetrator of the scam wishes the victim to work as a "mystery shopper", evaluating the service provided by MoneyGram or Western Union locations within major retailers such as Wal-Mart.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer sends the victim a forged or stolen cheque or money order as described above, the victim deposits it—banks will often credit an account with the value of a cheque not obviously false— and sends the money to the scammer via wire transfer.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Later the cheque is not honoured ("bounces") and the bank debits the victim's account.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Schemes based solely on cheque cashing usually offer only a small part of the cheque's total amount, with the assurance that many more cheques will follow; if the victim buys into the scam and cashes all the cheques, the scammer can steal a lot in a very short time.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] More sophisticated scams advertise jobs with real companies and offer lucrative salaries and conditions with the fraudsters pretending to be recruitment agents.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A bogus telephone or online interview may take place and after some time the applicant is informed that the job is theirs.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] To secure the job they are instructed to send money for their work visa or travel costs to the agent, or to a bogus travel agent who works on the scammer's behalf.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] No matter what the variation, they always involve the job seeker sending them or their agent money, credit card or bank account details.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A newer form of employment scam has arisen in which users are sent a bogus job offer but are not asked to give financial information.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Instead, their personal information is harvested during the application process and then sold to third parties for a profit, or used for identity theft.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Another form of employment scam involves making people attend a fake "interview" where they are told the benefits of the company.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The attendees are then made to assist to a conference where a scammer will use elaborate manipulation techniques to convince the attendees to purchase products, in a similar manner to the catalog merchant business model, as a hiring requisite.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Quite often, the company lacks any form of the physical catalog to help them sell products (e.g. jewelry).
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] When "given" the job, the individual is then asked to promote the scam job offer on their own.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They are also made to work for the company unpaid as a form of "training".
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Similar scams involve making alleged job candidates pay money upfront in person for training materials or services, with the claim that upon successful completion, they will be offered a guaranteed job, which never materializes.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The lottery scam involves fake notices of lottery wins, although the intended victim has not entered the lottery.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The "winner" is usually asked to send sensitive information such as name, residential address, occupation/position, lottery number etc. to a free email account which is at times untraceable or without any link.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In addition to harvesting this information, the scammer then notifies the victim that releasing the funds requires some small fee (insurance, registration, or shipping).
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Once the victim sends the fee, the scammer invents another fee.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The fake cheque technique described above is also used.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Fake or stolen cheque, representing a part payment of the winnings, being sent; then a fee, smaller than the amount received, is requested.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The bank receiving the bad cheque eventually reclaims the funds from the victim.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2004, a variant of the lottery scam appeared in the United States: a scammer phones a victim purporting to be speaking on behalf of the government about a grant they qualify for, subject to an advance fee of typically US$250.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Typical lottery scams address the person as some variation of *Lucky Winner*.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This is a red flag, as if someone entered an actual lottery and won, the organization would know their name, and not simply call them *Lucky Winner*.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Many scams involve the purchase of goods and services via classified advertisements, especially on sites like Craigslist, eBay, or Gumtree.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] These typically involve the scammer contacting the seller of a particular good or service via telephone or email expressing interest in the item.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They will typically then send a fake cheque written for an amount greater than the asking price, asking the seller to send the difference to an alternate address, usually by money order or Western Union.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A seller eager to sell a particular product may not wait for the cheque to clear, and when the bad cheque bounces, the funds wired have already been lost.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some scammers advertise phony academic conferences in exotic or international locations, complete with fake websites, scheduled agendas and advertising experts in a particular field that will be presenting there.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They offer to pay the airfare of the participants, but not the hotel accommodations.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They will extract money from the victims when they attempt to reserve their accommodations in a non-existent hotel.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Sometimes, an inexpensive rental property is advertised by a fake landlord, who is typically out of state (or the country) and asking for the rent and/or deposit to be wired to them.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Or the con artist finds a property, pretends to be the owner, lists it online, and communicates with the would-be renter to make a cash deposit.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer may also be the renter as well, in which case they pretend to be a foreign student and contact a landlord seeking accommodation.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They usually state they are not yet in the country and wish to secure accommodations prior to arriving.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Once the terms are negotiated, a forged cheque is forwarded for a greater amount than negotiated, and the fraudster asks the landlord to wire some of the money back.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This is a variation of the online sales scam where high-value, scarce pets are advertised as bait on online advertising websites using little real seller verification like Craigslist, Gumtree, and JunkMail.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The pet may either be advertised as being for-sale or up for adoption.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Typically, the pet is advertised on online advertising pages complete with photographs taken from various sources such as real advertisements, blogs or wherever else an image can be stolen.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Upon the potential victim contacting the scammer, the scammer responds by asking for details pertaining to the potential victim's circumstances and location under the pretense of ensuring that the pet would have a suitable home.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] By determining the location of the victim, the scammer ensures he is far enough from the victim so as to not allow the buyer to physically view the pet.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Should the scammer be questioned, as the advertisement claimed a location initially, the scammer will claim work circumstances having forced him to relocate.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This forces a situation whereby all communication is either via email, telephone (normally untraceable numbers) and SMS.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Upon the victim deciding to adopt or purchase the pet, a courier has to be used which is in reality part of the scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] If this is for an adopted pet, typically the victim is expected to pay some fee such as insurance, food or shipping.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Payment is via MoneyGram, Western Union or money mules' bank accounts where other victims have been duped into work from home scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Numerous problems are encountered in the courier phase of the scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The crate may be said to be too small, and the victim has the option of either purchasing a crate with air conditioning or renting one while also paying a deposit, typically called a caution or cautionary fee.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The victim may also have to pay for insurance if such fees have not been paid yet.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] If the victim pays these fees, the pet may be said to have become sick, and a veterinarian's assistance is sought for which the victim has to repay the courier.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Additionally, the victim may be asked to pay for a health certificate needed to transport the pet, and for kennel fees during the recuperation period.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The further the scam progresses, the more similar the fictitious fees are to those of typical 419 scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] It is not uncommon to see customs or like fees being claimed if such charges fit into the scam plot.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Numerous scam websites may be used for this scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This scam has been linked to the classical 419 scams in that the fictitious couriers used are also used in other types of 419 scams such as lotto scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] One of the variants is the *Romance Scam*, a money-for-romance angle.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The con artist approaches the victim on an online dating service, an instant messenger, or a social networking site.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer claims an interest in the victim, and posts pictures of an attractive person.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer uses this communication to gain confidence, then asks for money.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A very common example of romance scams is depicted in the fraudulent activities of these boys, popularly known as Yahoo boys in Nigeria.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The con artist may claim to be interested in meeting the victim but needs cash to book a plane, buy a bus ticket, rent a hotel room, pay for personal-travel costs such as gasoline or a vehicle rental, or to cover other expenses.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In other cases, they claim they are trapped in a foreign country and need assistance to return, to escape imprisonment by corrupt local officials, to pay for medical expenses due to an illness contracted abroad, and so on.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Scams often involve meeting someone on an online match-making service.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The scammer initiates contact with their target who is out of the area and requests money for transportation fare.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Scammers will typically ask for money to be sent via a money order or wire transfer due to the need to travel, or for medical or business costs.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] An extreme example of this is the case of a 67-year-old Australian woman, Jette Jacobs.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2013, she traveled to South Africa to supposedly marry her scammer, Jesse Orowo Omokoh, 28, after having sent more than $90,000 to him over a three-year period.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Her body was discovered on February 9, 2013, under mysterious circumstances, two days after meeting up with Omokoh, who then fled to Nigeria, where he was arrested.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] He was found to have had 32 fake online identities.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Due to lack of evidence he was not charged with murder, but was charged with fraud.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This variant of advance-fee fraud is widespread in India and Pakistan.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The fraudster uses Internet classified websites and print media to lure the public into installing a mobile phone tower on their property, with the promise of huge rental returns.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The fraudster also creates fake websites to appear legitimate.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The victims part with their money in pieces to the fraudster on account of the Government Service Tax, government clearance charges, bank charges, transportation charges, survey fee etc.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The Indian government is issuing public notices in media to spread awareness among the public and warn them against mobile tower fraudsters.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Other scams involve unclaimed property, also called "bona vacantia" in the United Kingdom.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In England and Wales (other than the Duchy of Lancaster and the Duchy of Cornwall), this property is administered by the Bona Vacantia Division of the Treasury Solicitor's Department.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Fraudulent emails and letters claiming to be from this department have been reported, informing the recipient they are the beneficiary of a legacy but requiring the payment of a fee before sending more information or releasing the money.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In the United States, messages are falsely claimed to be from the National Association of Unclaimed Property Administrators (NAUPA), a real organization, but one that does not and cannot by itself make payments.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In one variant of 419 fraud, an alleged hitman writes to someone explaining he has been targeted to kill them.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] He tells them he knows the allegations against them are false, and asks for money so the target can receive evidence of the person who ordered the hit.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Another variant of advanced fee fraud is known as a pigeon drop.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] This is a confidence trick in which the mark, or "pigeon", is persuaded to give up a sum of money in order to secure the rights to a larger sum of money, or more valuable object.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In reality, the scammers make off with the money and the mark is left with nothing.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In the process, the stranger (actually a confidence trickster) puts his money with the mark's money (in an envelope, briefcase, or bag) which the mark is then apparently entrusted with; it is actually switched for a bag full of newspaper or other worthless material.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Through various theatrics, the mark is given the opportunity to leave with the money without the stranger realizing.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In reality, the mark would be fleeing from his own money, which the con man still has (or has handed off to an accomplice).
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some scammers go after the victims of previous scams; known as a reloading scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] For example, they may contact a victim saying they can track and apprehend the scammer and recover the money lost by the victim for a price.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Or they may say a fund has been set up by the Nigerian government to compensate victims of 419 fraud, and all that is required is proof of the loss, personal information, and a processing and handling fee.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The recovery scammers obtain lists of victims by buying them from the original scammers.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Estimates of the total losses due to scams are uncertain and vary widely, since many people may be too embarrassed to admit that they were gullible enough to be scammed to report the crime.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A United States government report in 2006 indicated that Americans lost $198.4 million to Internet fraud in 2006, averaging a loss of $5,100 per incident.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] That same year, a report in the United Kingdom claimed that these scams cost the economy £150 million per year, with the average victim losing £31,000.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In addition to the financial cost, many victims also suffer a severe emotional and psychological cost, such as losing their ability to trust people.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] One man from Cambridgeshire, UK burnt himself to death with petrol after realizing that the $1.2 million "internet lottery" that he had won was actually a scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2007, a Chinese student at the University of Nottingham killed herself after she discovered that she had fallen for a similar lottery scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Other victims lose wealth and friends, become estranged from family members, deceive partners, get divorced, or commit criminal offenses in the process of either fulfilling their "obligations" to the scammers or obtaining more money.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2008, an Oregon woman lost $400,000 to a Nigerian advance-fee fraud scam, after an email told her she had inherited money from her long-lost grandfather.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Her curiosity was piqued because she actually had a grandfather with whom her family had lost touch, and whose initials matched those given in the email.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] She sent hundreds of thousands of dollars over a period of more than two years, despite her family, bank staff and law enforcement officials all urging her to stop.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The elderly are particularly susceptible to online scams such as this, as they typically come from a generation that was more trusting, and are often too proud to report the fraud.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] They also may be concerned that relatives might see it as a sign of declining mental capacity, and they are afraid to lose their independence.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Victims can be enticed to borrow or embezzle money to pay the advance fees, believing that they will shortly be paid a much larger sum and be able to refund what they had misappropriated.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Crimes committed by victims include credit-card fraud, check kiting, and embezzlement.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] San Diego–based businessman James Adler lost over $5 million in a Nigeria-based advance-fee scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Some 419 scams involve even more serious crimes, such as kidnapping or murder.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] One such case, in 2008, involves Osamai Hitomi, a Japanese businessman who was lured to Johannesburg, South Africa and kidnapped on September 26, 2008.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The kidnappers took him to Alberton, south of Johannesburg, and demanded a $5 million ransom from his family.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In July 2001, Joseph Raca, a former mayor of Northampton, UK, was kidnapped by scammers in Johannesburg, South Africa, who demanded a ransom of £20,000.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The captors released Raca after they became nervous.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The international nature of the crime, combined with the fact that many victims do not want to admit that they bought into an illegal activity, has made tracking down and apprehending these criminals difficult.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Furthermore, the government of Nigeria has been slow to take action, leading some investigators to believe that some Nigerian government officials are involved in some of these scams.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] The Nigeria government's establishment of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC) in 2004 helped with the issue to some degree, although issues with corruption remain.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Despite this, there have been some recent successes in apprehending and prosecuting these criminals.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2004, 52 suspects were arrested in Amsterdam after an extensive raid, after which almost no 419 emails were reported being sent by local internet service providers.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In November 2004, Australian authorities apprehended Nick Marinellis of Sydney, the self-proclaimed head of Australian 419ers who later boasted that he had "220 African brothers worldwide" and that he was "the Australian headquarters for those scams".
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] In 2008 US authorities in Olympia, Washington, sentenced Edna Fiedler to two years in prison with five years of supervised probation for her involvement in a $1 million Nigerian cheque scam.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] She had an accomplice in Lagos, Nigeria, who shipped her up to $1.1 million worth of counterfeit cheques and money orders with instructions on where to ship them.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Research suggests that some Nigerian hip-hop musicians have strong connections with some Yahoo Boys (cybercriminals).
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] Due to the increased use of the 419 scams on the Internet, it has been used as a plot device in many films, television shows and books.
[src:flour/advance-fee-scam] A song, "I Go Chop Your Dollar", performed by Nkem Owoh, also became internationally known as an anthem for 419 scammers using the phrases "419 is just a game, I am the winner, you are the loser".
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] These scams involve exploitation of the trust and friendship that exist in groups of people who have something in common.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Because of the tight-knit structure of many groups, it can be difficult for regulators or law enforcement officials to detect an affinity scam.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Victims often fail to notify authorities or pursue legal remedies, and instead try to work things out within the group.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] This is particularly true where the fraudsters have used respected community or religious leaders to convince others to join the investment.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Many affinity scams involve Ponzi schemes or pyramid schemes, where newly received investor money is used by the fraudster to make payments to earlier investors to give the illusion that the investment is successful.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] This ploy is used to trick new investors to invest in the scheme and to lull existing investors into believing their investments are safe and secure.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] In reality, the fraudster almost always steals investor money for personal use.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Both types of schemes depend on an unending supply of new investors; when the supply of investors inevitably dries up, the whole scheme collapses and investors discover that most or all of their money is gone.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Affinity frauds can involve the targeting of any group of people who take pride in their shared characteristics, whether they are religious, ethnic, or professional.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Securities and Exchange Commission have investigated and taken action against affinity frauds targeting a wide spectrum of groups.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] On December 11, 2008, Bernard Madoff, an American businessman, was arrested on charges of securities fraud, having been turned in by his sons after allegedly telling them his business was a "giant ponzi scheme".
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] According to the New York Post, Madoff "worked the so-called 'Jewish circuit' of well-heeled Jews he met at country clubs on Long Island and in Palm Beach." Additionally, one of Madoff's middlemen was J.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Freedman of *The New York Times*, Merkin was prominent in the Modern Orthodox community.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] This allowed him to defraud institutions such as Yeshiva University, Kehilath Jeshurun Synagogue, the Maimonides School, Ramaz and the SAR Academy.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] On July 27, 2009, Earl Jones was arrested for fraud in Montreal.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] His clients were English-speaking elderly in Quebec where the majority speak French as their first language.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] On August 14, 2009, *CTV* and *CBC Radio One News* reported that investors with Hershey Rosen are also suspected of being defrauded.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Like the Jones investors, they too are English-speaking Quebeckers.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] A 2012 article in *The Economist* reports that Utah is believed to have the highest per-capita rate of affinity fraud in the U.S. due to about two-thirds of the state's residents being members of the LDS Church among whom such crimes tend to flourish.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Authorities estimate affinity fraud cost Utahns an estimated $1.4 billion in 2010 alone, an average of about $500 per resident.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] Salt Lake City attorney Mark Pugsley (who specializes in representing white-collar fraud cases) reports that Utah County is the hotbed of financial fraud in the state, particularly the roughly 25-mile corridor from Alpine through Provo.
[src:flour/affinity-fraud] In 2017, a statement from the FBI noted that Utah consistently ranked high in the states with "the most significant white-collar crime cases" and that Utah state legislature established an online registry for convicted fraudsters, hoping to prevent repeat offenses and inform the public.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The building was designed by the architect Samuel Wyatt.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The engines were supplied with water taken directly from the River Thames.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] At the time, they were "the most complete and powerful which had been produced by the Soho Manufactory".
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The mill's wheels and shafts were made of iron.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] An exception to this were some of the cogs, which were of hard wood, though others were of cast iron, as were the pinions.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The teeth, some of wood and others of iron, were manufactured by chipping and filing into epicycloidal shapes.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The shafts and axles were made of iron and the bearings of brass.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The mill's double engine, producing 50 horsepower (37 kW), drove 20 pairs of millstones, each grinding some nine bushels of corn an hour.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] It also provided power for raising corn, fanning it to free it of impurities, sifting it, dressing the meal and lowering it into the barges, which made the process more efficient.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The mill was built in 1786 by Matthew Boulton, with the backing of City financiers and Joah Bates, an organ player and composer who "embarked all his own money and 10,000/ belonging to his wife" to build it.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] It was the first steam-powered commercial flour mill in the United Kingdom.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] James Watt, an associate of Boulton, was personally hired to build a steam engine for the mill to grind corn.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] Watt's engine was tested before numerous spectators, including Sir Joseph Banks, but encountered problems with the sun and planet gear, and the piston rods.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The cost of erecting the mill proved to be considerably in excess of the original estimate, and Watt soon feared that it would turn out to be a losing concern.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] He had no doubt that the engines or the machinery would be able to do all that had been promised; but he feared that the absence of business capacity on the part of the managers would be fatal to the mill's commercial success.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] In September 1786, the Duke of Milan visited the mills.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] By 1789, a second engine had been installed.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The business thrived, and by June 1790 the mill was producing sales of £6,800 in flour a week.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] However, problems remained with its running and maintenance, and Boulton was dissatisfied with the results.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] At 06:30 on 2 March 1791, a fire gutted the building, devastating Bates financially.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] The building was completely gutted within two hours.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] Several houses near the mills were also burnt down.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] Arson was strongly suspected, but John Rennie and Wyatt, the manager of the mill, blamed a lack of grease on a corn machine in front of the kiln, and called the fire an accident.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] In response to the loss of the Albion Mills, the proprietors of mills at Blackwall, Limehouse and Poplar, Middlesex and Rotherhithe, Surrey restarted business, their mills having been idle for more than three years.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] According to Graham Gibberd, the Albion Mills building became "London's symbol for the impending industrial revolution", and the shell of the building was the inspiration for William Blake's "dark satanic mills" in his poem *And did those feet in ancient time*.
[src:flour/albion-mills-southwark] Most of the notable engineering drawings and depictions of the Albion Mills are in the Boulton & Watt Archive of Birmingham Central Library.
[src:flour/almond-meal] It is used in pastry and confectionery – in the manufacture of almond macarons and macaroons and other sweet pastries, in cake and pie filling, such as Austrian *Sachertorte* – and is one of the two main ingredients of marzipan and almond paste.
[src:flour/almond-meal] In France, almond meal is an important ingredient in *frangipane*, the filling of traditional *galette des Rois* cake.
[src:flour/almond-meal] Almond meal has recently become important in baking items for those on low-carbohydrate diets.
[src:flour/almond-meal] It adds moistness and a rich nutty taste to baked goods.
[src:flour/almond-meal] Items baked with almond meal tend to be calorie-dense.
[src:flour/almond-meal] Almonds have high levels of polyunsaturated fats.
[src:flour/almond-meal] Typically, the omega 6 fatty acids in almonds are protected from oxidation by the surface skin and vitamin E.
[src:flour/almond-meal] When almonds are ground, this protective skin is broken and exposed surface area increases dramatically, greatly enhancing the nut's tendency to oxidize.
[src:flour/alveograph] The **Chopin Alveograph** (originally named **Extensimeter**) is an empirical tool for wheat flour quality measurement.
[src:flour/alveograph] It measures the properties of the dough produced from the flour, by inflating a bubble in a thin sheet of the dough until it bursts.
[src:flour/alveograph] This process is supposed to simulate the natural bubble growth during the fermentation and in the early stages of baking.
[src:flour/alveograph] An analysis of the recorded graph of pressure vs. bubble volume yields about ten values that characterize the suitability of the flour for different uses.
[src:flour/alveograph] As of the 2020s, the device is manufactured by **Chopin Technologies** (since 2016, a part of KPM Analytics).
[src:flour/alveograph] A similar device for bubble inflation, D/R Dough Inflation System, is made by Stable Micro Systems.
[src:flour/alveograph] The idea of wheat grain classification by using a bubble made of dough dates back to 1905, when a Hungarian, Jenö von Hankoczy, created a "gluten tester".
[src:flour/alveograph] The tester measured only the maximum expansion of the bubble before bursting and, as other early devices, had no temperature control.
[src:flour/alveograph] Developed independently in the late 1920s in France by Marcel Chopin, the Chopin Alveograph performs the *alveographic test* that enables to measure the tenacity (resilience), extensibility, and elasticity of a dough (standardized mix of flour and water).
[src:flour/alveograph] This measurement, known as dough strength, is considered as a good index of the baking quality of baking flours.
[src:flour/alveograph] The original "extensimeter" design by Chopin was created in 1921 and tested the tenacity of dough (then defined as time it took to change the shape of a cylinder made of dough) and the ability of the sample to be stretched into a thin membrane by pushing air into the sample.
[src:flour/alveograph] The extensimeter had temperature control since the original model, a version with a better recorder came out in 1927.
[src:flour/alveograph] By the mid-1930s, an integrated dough mixer was added.
[src:flour/alveograph] In 1982, an air pump was introduced to pump up the bubble instead of using the gravity of a column of water to expel the air.
[src:flour/alveograph] In 1987, a timer and temperature display were added, bubble blowing was automated in the 1995 model.
[src:flour/alveograph] A completely new design, so called "NG", was introduced in 1995 and included a consistograph.
[src:flour/alveograph] In France it has been used in regulations since at least 1963 as a criterion in milling for the composition of flours destined to the "french" type bread-baking.
[src:flour/alveograph] KPM Analytics produces a derivative device called the Mixolab which, among other uses, measures the degree of degradation due to pest and fungus, and the protection provided by insecticides and fungicides.
[src:flour/alveograph] 2. an alveograph itself (the bubble-blowing device) which measures the three-dimensional extension of the piece of dough, which is deformed like a bubble.
[src:flour/alveograph] That extension mode reproduces the deformation of the dough under the influence of the pushing of gas.
[src:flour/alveograph] The test is performed by slowly inflating the bubble and recording the pressure H (expressed in mm of water) vs. abscissa L (that is also expressed in millimeters, but in reality is just time from the start of the test in seconds converted into mm at a fixed rate of 5.5 mm/s).
[src:flour/alveograph] The correction coefficients are applied for compatibility with the earlier models.
[src:flour/alveograph] Originally, the following results were collected from the pressure graph: maximum overpressure (P), average abscissa to rupture (L), swelling index (G), configuration ratio (P/L) and deformation energy (W).
[src:flour/alveograph] After the introduction of computerized processing, more parameters were added, like the elasticity index (Ie), and minimum and maximum of first derivative (Dmin/Dmax).
[src:flour/alveograph] Pressure curve was converted into the stress–strain curve, yielding the strain hardening index (SH) and the strength coefficient (K).
[src:flour/alveograph] Jødal & Larsen (2021) suggest that G, Dmax, SH and K are near-perfectly correlated to L, P, Ie and P respectively, thus the basic set of parameters obtained on the alveograph contains just six values: P, L, W, P/L, Ie and Dmin.
[src:flour/alveograph] The measurements are typically repeated multiple times and averaged.
[src:flour/alveograph] The maximum overpressure is the highest pressure that occurs during the test, multiplied by 1.1 (the coefficient accommodates the measurement error introduced by a water manometer of the earliest models).
[src:flour/alveograph] P is called the dough "tenacity", often used, but has no corresponding rheological value and thus is interpreted in multiple ways.
[src:flour/alveograph] The bursting of the bubble is manifested by a rapid decline in pressure (right side of the graph).
[src:flour/alveograph] The corresponding abscissa point, L, is called "extensibility", and characterizes the maximum stretch that dough can experience without breaking.
[src:flour/alveograph] It is an important parameter in breadmaking, as high values of L make possible breads with high volume and fine crumb structure.
[src:flour/alveograph] The swelling index G expresses the volume of air (in milliliters) needed to rupture the bubble.
[src:flour/alveograph] Since the air is fed at a constant rate, G is a square root of L (in mm) with a scaling coefficient that, depending on the version of the manual, is either 2.22 or 2.226: $G=2.226{\sqrt {L}}$ .
[src:flour/alveograph] It has the same significance as L, yet also is considered to be affecting the "shortness" and "spring" of the dough.
[src:flour/alveograph] The product of force (pressure) and time is energy, thus the area under the pressure curve is proportional to the energy used to inflate the bubble, or deformation energy W.
[src:flour/alveograph] **W factor** is one of the most used values for the characterization of wheat (separating wheat cultivars), and is referred to as "strength" (dough strength, flour strength, baking strength, flour protein strength, gluten strength, etc).
[src:flour/alveograph] W is closely related to the percentage and quality of gluten in the dough, but is also affected by other factors, including the water absorption.
[src:flour/alveograph] Strong dough can withstand the mechanical stress of the breadmaking process through a balanced combination of viscosity and elasticity.
[src:flour/alveograph] The value is typically expressed in Joules (J) units.
[src:flour/alveograph] Due to numbers being low, a scaling factor is frequently used (the practical units are $J\cdot 10^{-4}$ ), bringing the typical values into a three-digit range.
[src:flour/alveograph] The ratio of P to L is called the *configuration ratio*.
[src:flour/alveograph] The high ratio reflects a strong and inextensible dough, while low values correspond to a weak and extensible one.
[src:flour/alveograph] While P/L seems to characterize a balance between tenacity and extensibility, the P/L requirements frequently do not change across the areas of use, and it is less frequently used.
[src:flour/alveograph] The elasticity index Ie is defined as ratio of pressure corresponding to the 40 mm abscissa and the maximum overpressure P, expressed as percentage: $Ie={\frac {H_{40mm}}{P}}\cdot 100\%$ .
[src:flour/alveograph] Since the volume of air pumped into the bubble at this point in time is about 200 ml, the 40 mm pressure is also denoted as P200, so $Ie={\frac {P_{200}}{P}}\cdot 100\%$ For more extensible doughs, the pressure might never reach 40 mm, and Ie cannot be determined.
[src:flour/alveograph] The 40 mm abscissa is selected to reflect the moment when the resistance to deformation is expected to no longer depend on the thickness of dough and thus reflect the internal bonding force.
[src:flour/alveograph] There is a positive correlation had been found between the Ie and the bread volume.
[src:flour/alveograph] A first derivate can be taken of the pressure curve, the minimum and maximum values of the derivative are denoted Dmin and Dmax respectively.
[src:flour/alveograph] Dmin thus defined is negative, so sometimes an absolute value is used.
[src:flour/alveograph] Lower Dmin values correlate to higher volume of bread.
[src:flour/alveograph] Dmax, while reported by the alveograph, is apparently not used in practice.
[src:flour/alveograph] The relationship between stress $\sigma$ and Hencky strain $\epsilon$ can be described by a stress-strain curve $\sigma =K\cdot e^{{SH}\cdot \epsilon }$ , where SH and K are empirical coefficients best-fit using the alveograph curve.
[src:flour/alveograph] The exponential part of the equation reflects the strain hardening caused by the properties of gluten network.
[src:flour/alveograph] High SH improves the condition for inflation of dough bubbles in the bread.
[src:flour/alveograph] K defines the stress when there is no strain.
[src:flour/alveograph] It is higher for more stiff or viscous dough and, probably due this mixing of two different properties in one value, used less frequently than SH.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The AWB was founded in 1939 to regulate the wheat market after the excesses of the Great Depression.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This type of arrangement was not unique to Australia, as the Canadian Wheat Board was created in 1935 in a similar fashion (but its history dates back to an earlier wheat marketing board created during World War I, and also includes the experience of cooperative wheat pools during the 1920s).
[src:flour/awb-limited] For much of its early history, it was a government-run and owned company.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In July 1999, it was restructured as a private company.
[src:flour/awb-limited] It offered "class A" shares to those who met its definition of growers and who had the ability to elect the majority of its board and chairperson, and from August 2001, 'class B' were publicly traded on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In 2008, constitutional amendments were passed.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Despite resistance from several wheat lobbies and industry groups, it consolidated ownership of AWB into one type of share, giving growers no special consideration.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This change was proposed by the AWB management as necessarily to having a simpler, lower-risk business model.
[src:flour/awb-limited] After privatisation, AWB grew to incorporate a number of subsidiaries to diversify its income away from its wheat exports.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Its subsidiary businesses include GrainFlow to manage collection of grain from farmers to ports, companies to ship the grain overseas to customers, and Landmark rural services.
[src:flour/awb-limited] AWB Limited was a holding company owning a number of subsidiaries.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Its shares were freely traded on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:flour/awb-limited] AWB Limited had a number of subsidiaries.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Some of these subsidiaries existed due to legislative requirements relating to the operation of the single desk; others exist for the purpose of controlling credit risk.
[src:flour/awb-limited] AWB announced a new strategy in 2009 to simplify and de-risk the business.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This resulted in the divestment of the financial services loan book to the ANZ Bank in December 2009.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In March 2010, AWB announced the signing of a memorandum of understanding to sell the Geneva business and to joint venture the local grain trading business.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Previously a low profile organisation, the AWB made headlines in late 2005 when it was alleged that it had knowingly paid kickbacks to the Iraq Government, in violation of United Nations sanctions and Australian law.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the United Nations had imposed a financial and trade embargo on Iraq.
[src:flour/awb-limited] However, after facing criticism over the humanitarian impacts of the sanctions, the UN from 1995 until late 2003 allowed Iraq to trade oil on the world market in exchange for food, medicine and other humanitarian needs.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Despite this, at the insistence of the Iraq government of dictator Saddam Hussein, the AWB agreed to pay "transportation fees" of around $A$290 million.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This money was paid to a Jordanian transportation company, Alia.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Alia kept a small percentage of the fees, and paid the remainder onto Saddam's government.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This breached the sanctions placed on the Iraqi regime.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The government-sanctioned Cole Inquiry into the company's role in the scandal has been completed and was tabled by Attorney-General Philip Ruddock on 27 November 2006.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The report found that, from mid-1999, AWB had knowingly entered into an arrangement that involved paying kickbacks to the Iraqi government, in order to retain its business.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The Inquiry recommended that 12 people be investigated for possible criminal and corporations offences over the scandal.
[src:flour/awb-limited] At the height of the investigation, the single-desk arrangement from which AWB benefits came under criticism.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In 2006, the Australian Grain Exporters Association asked the Government to remove AWB's monopoly export powers.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The oil-for-wheat scandal cast doubt among some grain exporters over the trust placed in the company, especially as they lost the ability to export to Iraq during the length of the Cole Inquiry, losing one of their biggest markets.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The scandal resulted in international condemnation and litigation.
[src:flour/awb-limited] On 11 July 2006, North American farmers claimed $1 billion in damages from AWB at Washington DC, alleging the Australian wheat exporter used bribery and other corrupt activities to corner grain markets.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The growers claimed that AWB used the same techniques to secure grain sales in other markets in Asia and other countries in the Middle East.
[src:flour/awb-limited] The lawsuit was dismissed in March 2007.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In August 2009, the Australian Federal Police dropped their investigation into any criminal actions undertaken by AWB and others in this matter.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This decision came after Paul Hastings QC declared the prospect of convictions was limited and "not in the public interest".
[src:flour/awb-limited] The Australian Securities & Investments Commission then proceeded with several civil cases against six former directors and officers of AWB.
[src:flour/awb-limited] AWB's former managing director Andrew Lindberg and former chief financial officer Paul Ingleby were ultimately fined and banned from managing a company for one year.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Former chairman Trevor Flugge was also fined, and banned from managing a company for five years.
[src:flour/awb-limited] A civil suit brought by shareholders of AWB was settled out of court for $39.5 million in February 2010.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Australia's government has distanced itself from the payments to Saddam Hussein's regime, given Australia's contribution to military action against Hussein in the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Andrew Lindberg resigned as managing director on 9 February 2006 and from the board of directors on 22 February 2006 under intense public and media pressure.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In the years immediately following the Cole Inquiry, AWB continued to be dogged by bad performance.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Following the publication of the Cole Inquiry, a new management team was installed under the leadership of Gordon Davis who was recruited from Orica in August 2006.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Davis successfully reformed the constitution and the shareholder structure to consolidate into 1 class of shareholder.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This new management team has not been entirely without controversy.
[src:flour/awb-limited] On 26 April 2007, Yahoo News reported that AWB also breached US sanctions on Iran.
[src:flour/awb-limited] These sanctions prohibit American citizens and companies using American currency from trading with Iran.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In 2006, AWB's US subsidiary attempted to pay an Iranian transport company approximately $1 million, in clear breach of the US sanctions.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In 2009, the company faced difficulties in another new market, when it was forced to recapitalise the balance sheet after the company produced significant losses from the expansion of trading activities into Brazil under Davis.
[src:flour/awb-limited] Despite making a small profit in 2009, in March 2010, the company announced a profit downgrade from domestic trading activities.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In May 2010, it reported a half-year loss of $64.8 million, which it claimed due to the cost of settling the shareholder class action for $39.5m, and a loss of $65.4m on restructuring costs associated with its sale of the Landmark Financial Services loan and deposit books.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In July 2010, AWB entered into an agreement to merge with GrainCorp.
[src:flour/awb-limited] This did not proceed, after Agrium made a successful takeover offer that was completed in December 2010, with the company delisted from the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:flour/awb-limited] In 2011, Cargill acquired the AWB Commodity Management business from Agrium.
[src:flour/flour] Cereal flour, particularly wheat flour, is the main ingredient of bread, which is a staple food for many cultures.
[src:flour/flour] Archaeologists have found evidence of humans making cereal flour over 32,000 years ago.
[src:flour/flour] Other cereal flours include corn flour, which has been important in Mesoamerican cuisine since ancient times and remains a staple in the Americas, while rye flour is a constituent of bread in both Central Europe and Northern Europe.
[src:flour/flour] Cereal flour consists either of the endosperm, germ, and bran together, known as whole-grain flour, or of the endosperm alone, which is known as refined flour.
[src:flour/flour] 'Meal' is technically differentiable from flour as having slightly coarser particle size, known as degree of comminution.
[src:flour/flour] However, the word 'meal' is synonymous with 'flour' in some parts of the world.
[src:flour/flour] The processing of cereal flour to produce white flour, where the outer layers are removed, means nutrients are lost.
[src:flour/flour] Such flour, and the breads made from them, may be fortified by adding nutrients.
[src:flour/flour] As of 2016, it is a legal requirement in 86 countries to fortify wheat flour.
[src:flour/flour] Nut flour is made by grinding blanched nuts, except for walnut flour, for which the oil is extracted first.
[src:flour/flour] Nut flour is a popular gluten-free alternative, being used within the "keto" and "paleo" diets.
[src:flour/flour] None of the nuts' nutritional benefits are lost during the grinding process.
[src:flour/flour] Nut flour has traditionally been used in Mediterranean and Persian cuisine.
[src:flour/flour] Bean flours are made by grinding beans that have been either dried or roasted.
[src:flour/flour] Commonly used bean flours include chickpea, also known as gram flour or besan, made from dried chickpeas and traditionally used in Mediterranean, Middle Eastern and Indian cuisine.
[src:flour/flour] Soybean flour is made by soaking the beans to dehull them, before they are dried (or roasted to make kinako) and ground down; at least 97% of the product must pass through a 100-mesh standard screen to be called soya flour, which is used in many Asian cuisines.
[src:flour/flour] Seed flours like teff are traditional to Ethiopia and Eritrea, where they are used to make flatbread and sourdough, while buckwheat has been traditionally used in Russia, Japan and Italy.
[src:flour/flour] In Australia, millstones to grind seed have been found that date from the Pleistocene period.
[src:flour/flour] Root flours include arrowroot and cassava.
[src:flour/flour] Arrowroot flour (also known as arrowroot powder) is used as a thickener in sauces, soups and pies, and has twice the thickening power of wheat flour.
[src:flour/flour] Cassava flour is gluten-free and used as an alternative to wheat flour.
[src:flour/flour] Cassava flour is traditionally used in African, South and Central American and Caribbean food.
[src:flour/flour] Vegetable flour is made from vegetables that are dehydrated before they are milled.
[src:flour/flour] These can be made from most vegetables, including broccoli, spinach, squash and green peas.
[src:flour/flour] They are rich in fibre and are gluten-free.
[src:flour/flour] There have been studies to see if vegetable flour can be added to wheat-flour-based bread as an alternative to using other enrichment methods.
[src:flour/flour] The English word *flour* is originally a variant of the word *flower*, and both words derive from the Old French *fleur* or *flour*, which had the literal meaning "blossom", and a figurative meaning "the finest".
[src:flour/flour] The phrase *fleur de farine* meant "the finest part of the flour", since flour resulted from the elimination of coarse and unwanted matter from the grain during milling.
[src:flour/flour] Maize or corn flour has been important in Mesoamerican cuisine since ancient times and remains a staple in the Americas.
[src:flour/flour] Rye flour is a constituent of bread in central and northern Europe.
[src:flour/flour] Archaeological evidence for making wheat flour dates to at least 6000 BC.
[src:flour/flour] In Australia, excavations at the site of Madjedbebe found grindstone used to grind seed dating from the Pleistocene period.
[src:flour/flour] In 2018, archaeologists reported finding evidence of bread making at Shubayqa 1, a Natufian hunter-gatherer site more than 14,000 years old in northwest Jordan.
[src:flour/flour] The Romans were the first to grind cereals on cone mills.
[src:flour/flour] In 1786, at the beginning of the Industrial Era, the first steam-powered flour mill, Albion Mills, Southwark, was completed in London.
[src:flour/flour] In the 1930s, some flour began to be enriched with iron, niacin, thiamine and riboflavin.
[src:flour/flour] In the 1940s, mills started to enrich flour and folic acid was added to the list in the 1990s.
[src:flour/flour] An important problem of the Industrial Revolution was the preservation of flour.
[src:flour/flour] Transportation distances and a relatively slow distribution system collided with natural shelf life.
[src:flour/flour] The reason for the limited shelf life is the fatty acids of the germ, which react from the moment they are exposed to oxygen.
[src:flour/flour] This occurs when grain is milled; the fatty acids oxidize and flour starts to become rancid.
[src:flour/flour] Depending on climate and grain quality, this process takes six to nine months.
[src:flour/flour] In the late 19th century, this process was too short for an industrial production and distribution cycle.
[src:flour/flour] As vitamins, micronutrients and amino acids were completely or relatively unknown in the late 19th century, removing the germ was an effective solution.
[src:flour/flour] Without the germ, flour cannot become rancid.
[src:flour/flour] Degermation started in densely populated areas and took approximately one generation to reach the countryside.
[src:flour/flour] Heat-processed flour is flour where the germ is first separated from the endosperm and bran, then processed with steam, dry heat or microwave and blended into flour again.
[src:flour/flour] Milling of flour is accomplished by grinding grain between stones or steel wheels.
[src:flour/flour] Today, "stone-ground" usually means that the grain has been ground in a mill in which a revolving stone wheel turns over a stationary stone wheel, vertically or horizontally with the grain in between.
[src:flour/flour] Roller mills replaced stone grist mills in the 19th century.
[src:flour/flour] The production of flour has historically driven technological development, as attempts to make gristmills and flour mills more productive and less labor-intensive led to the watermill and windmill.
[src:flour/flour] These terms are now applied more broadly to uses of water and wind power for purposes other than milling.
[src:flour/flour] More recently, the Unifine mill, an impact-type mill, was developed in the mid-20th century.
[src:flour/flour] Flour contains a high proportion of starches, which are a subset of complex carbohydrates also known as polysaccharides.
[src:flour/flour] The kinds of flour used in cooking include all-purpose (North America) or plain flour, self-rising (North America) or self-raising flour, and, in North America, cake flour.
[src:flour/flour] The higher the protein content, the harder and stronger the flour, and the more it will produce crispy or chewy breads.
[src:flour/flour] The lower the protein, the softer the flour, which is better for cakes, cookies, and pie crusts.
[src:flour/flour] Cereal flour consists either of the endosperm, germ, and bran together (whole-grain flour) or of the endosperm alone (refined flour).
[src:flour/flour] "Bleached flour" is "refined" flour with a chemical whitening (bleaching) agent added.
[src:flour/flour] "Refined" flour has had the germ and bran, containing much of the nutritional fibre and vitamins, removed and is often referred to as "white flour".
[src:flour/flour] Bleached flour is artificially aged using a "bleaching" agent, a "maturing" agent, or both.
[src:flour/flour] A bleaching agent affects the carotenoids responsible for the natural colour of the flour; a "maturing" agent also affects gluten development.
[src:flour/flour] A maturing agent may either strengthen or weaken gluten development.
[src:flour/flour] This is still available in North America, but has been banned in Europe, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:flour/flour] All bleaching and maturing agents (with the possible exception of ascorbic acid) have been banned in the United Kingdom.
[src:flour/flour] Bromination of flour in the US has fallen out of favor, and while it is not yet actually banned anywhere, few retail flours available to the home baker are bromated anymore.
[src:flour/flour] Many varieties of flour packaged specifically for commercial bakeries are still bromated.
[src:flour/flour] Retail bleached flour marketed to the home baker is now treated mostly with either peroxidation or chlorine gas.
[src:flour/flour] Current information from Pillsbury is that their varieties of bleached flour are treated both with benzoyl peroxide and chlorine gas.
[src:flour/flour] Gold Medal states that their bleached flour is treated either with benzoyl peroxide or chlorine gas, but no way exists to tell which process has been used when buying the flour at the grocery store.
[src:flour/flour] The old method of procuring white or "bleached" flour did not entail the use of chemical agents at all.
[src:flour/flour] Rather, the wheat kernels were moistened with water long enough for the outer kernels of the wheat which contained the bran to soften and, eventually, fall off while grinding.
[src:flour/flour] During the process of making flour, specifically as a result of the bleaching process, nutrients are lost.
[src:flour/flour] Some of these nutrients may be replaced during refining – the result is known as *enriched* flour.
[src:flour/flour] In the UK most flour, and consequently breads made with it, is required to be fortified with added calcium, iron, thiamine (Vitamin B1) and niacin (Vitamin B3); wholemeal flour is exempt as it inherently contains sufficient of these nutrients.
[src:flour/flour] Cake flour is the lowest in gluten protein content, with 6–7% (5–8% from second source) protein to produce minimal binding so the cake "crumbles" easily.
[src:flour/flour] Pastry flour has the second-lowest gluten protein content, with 7.5–9.5% (8–9% from second source) protein to hold together with a bit more strength than cakes, but still produce flaky crusts rather than hard or crispy ones.
[src:flour/flour] All-purpose, or "AP flour", or plain flour is medium in gluten protein content at 9.5–11.5% (10–12% from second source) protein content.
[src:flour/flour] It has adequate protein content for many bread and pizza bases, though bread flour and special 00 grade Italian flour are often preferred for these purposes, respectively, especially by artisan bakers.
[src:flour/flour] Some biscuits are also prepared using this type of flour.
[src:flour/flour] "Plain" refers not only to AP flour's middling gluten content but also to its lack of any added leavening agent (as in self-rising flour).
[src:flour/flour] Bread flour is typically made from hard red winter wheat planted in the fall and harvested in the spring.
[src:flour/flour] Hard wheat is high in gluten, a protein that makes dough stretchy.
[src:flour/flour] The increased protein binds to the flour to entrap carbon dioxide released by the yeast fermentation process, resulting in a better rise and chewier texture.
[src:flour/flour] Hard is a general term for flours with high gluten protein content, commonly refers to extra strong flour, with 13.5–16% (or 14–15% from some sources) protein (16% is a theoretically possible protein content).
[src:flour/flour] This flour may be used where a recipe adds ingredients that require the dough to be extra strong to hold together in their presence, or when strength is needed for constructions of bread (e.g., some centerpiece displays).
[src:flour/flour] Gluten flour is refined gluten protein, or a theoretical 100% protein (though practical refining never achieves a full 100%).
[src:flour/flour] It is used to strengthen flour as needed.
[src:flour/flour] For example, adding approximately one teaspoon per cup of AP flour gives the resulting mix the protein content of bread flour.
[src:flour/flour] It is commonly added to whole grain flour recipes to overcome the tendency of greater fiber content to interfere with gluten development, needed to give the bread better rising (gas holding) qualities and chew.
[src:flour/flour] Unbleached flour is simply flour that has not undergone bleaching and therefore does not have the color of "white" flour.
[src:flour/flour] An example is graham flour, whose namesake, Sylvester Graham, was against using bleaching agents, which he considered unhealthy.
[src:flour/flour] In English-speaking countries, self-raising (or self-rising in North America) flour is commercially available with chemical leavening agents already in the mix.
[src:flour/flour] In America, it is also likely to be pre-salted; in Britain this is not the case.
[src:flour/flour] The added ingredients are evenly distributed throughout the flour, which aids a consistent rise in baked goods.
[src:flour/flour] This flour is generally used for preparing amongst others sponge cakes, scones and muffins.
[src:flour/flour] It was invented by Henry Jones and patented in 1845.
[src:flour/flour] Wheat is the most preferred cereal grain used to make flour.
[src:flour/flour] Flours can contain differing levels of the protein gluten.
[src:flour/flour] "Strong flour" or "hard flour" has a higher gluten content than "weak" or "soft" flour.
[src:flour/flour] "Brown" and wholemeal flours may be made of hard or soft wheat.
[src:flour/flour] When flours do not contain gluten, they are suitable for people with gluten-related disorders, such as coeliac disease, non-celiac gluten sensitivity or wheat allergy, among others.
[src:flour/flour] Contamination with gluten-containing cereals can occur during grain harvesting, transporting, milling, storing, processing, handling and/or cooking.
[src:flour/flour] Flour also can be made from soybeans, arrowroot, taro, cattails, manioc, quinoa, and other non-cereal foodstuffs.
[src:flour/flour] Flour dust suspended in air is explosive—as is any mixture of a finely powdered flammable substance with air.
[src:flour/flour] Some devastating explosions have occurred at flour mills, including the Tradeston Flour Mills, in Glasgow, Scotland, which exploded in 1872 killing eighteen people, and an explosion in 1878 at the Washburn "A" Mill in Minneapolis that killed 22 people.
[src:flour/flour] In the US, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has cautioned not to eat raw flour doughs or batters.
[src:flour/flour] Raw flour could contain harmful bacteria such as *E. coli* that were possibly in the ground when the cereal was growing.
[src:flour/flour] It is recommended that flour should be cooked like other foods to kill the bacteria.
[src:flour/flour] Similar advice has been issued by food standard agencies across the world.
[src:flour/flour] During the industrial revolution, wheat and corn flour fraud became more common as it was mixed with chalk or gypsum dust.
[src:flour/flour] Bread, pasta, crackers, cakes, and several other foods are made using flour.
[src:flour/flour] Wheat or corn flour is also used to make a roux as a base for thickening gravy and sauces.
[src:flour/flour] It can also be used as an ingredient in papier-mâché glue.
[src:flour/flour] Cornstarch is a principal ingredient used to thicken many puddings or desserts, and is the main ingredient in packaged custard.
